    "narrative": "For the April 24th slate, the Zurich Zebras lean heavily on **Yordan Alvarez** (70.94) and **Junior Caminero** (70.65), our premier options against Warren and Bradley, respectively. Both benefit from high-leverage batting order positioning; the +8% boost for **Yordan Alvarez** at the #2 spot, paired with his robust 0.393 xwOBA, cements him as our primary anchor. **Junior Caminero** faces a tougher park environment, but his SP Skill adjustment of +11% validates his selection as a must-start. **Trea Turner** (68.42) remains our most critical asset for stolen base accumulation; his +10% order bonus as the leadoff hitter, combined with a favorable matchup against Holmes, provides the highest ceiling for the scarcity category we prioritize. Meanwhile, **Caleb Durbin** (67.42) surges into the starting lineup thanks to a significant +16% park factor and +16% SP skill adjustment, making him the most efficient utilization of our MI slot despite the #8 lineup anchor.\n\nThe most difficult benching decision involved **Pete Crow-Armstrong** (50.22), who offered intrigue due to his +14% dynamic platoon edge. However, the optimizer remained skeptical of the sub-optimal #9 spot and a challenging matchup against the arm of Sheehan, which carried a -19% SP skill penalty. We are navigating a precarious day for **Josh Smith** (57.10) and **Hyeseong Kim** (57.50), both of whom are suppressed by batting order penalties. While **Dillon Dingler** (61.29) provides a solid floor at catcher, his score is bolstered significantly by a +14% dynamic platoon edge against the lefty Abbott. We are monitoring **Pete Crow-Armstrong** closely as a pivot if lineups shift, but for now, the roster remains set to maximize efficiency while managing our game cap constraints. All starters are healthy, and we remain cautious of the volatility inherent in the middle-to-bottom of our order.",
